# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermocouples
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The **Seebeck coefficient** (also known as **thermopower**, **thermoelectric power**, and **thermoelectric sensitivity**) of a material is a measure of the magnitude of an induced thermoelectric voltage in response to a temperature difference across that material, as induced by the Seebeck effect.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The SI unit of the Seebeck coefficient is volts per kelvin (V/K), although it is more often given in microvolts per kelvin (μV/K).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The use of materials with a high Seebeck coefficient is one of many important factors for the efficient behaviour of thermoelectric generators and thermoelectric coolers.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] More information about high-performance thermoelectric materials can be found in the Thermoelectric materials article.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In thermocouples the Seebeck effect is used to measure temperatures, and for accuracy it is desirable to use materials with a Seebeck coefficient that is stable over time.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Physically, the magnitude and sign of the Seebeck coefficient can be approximately understood as being given by the entropy per unit charge carried by electrical currents in the material.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In conductors that can be understood in terms of independently moving, nearly-free charge carriers, the Seebeck coefficient is negative for negatively charged carriers (such as electrons), and positive for positively charged carriers (such as electron holes).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] One way to define the Seebeck coefficient is the voltage built up when a small temperature gradient is applied to a material, and when the material has come to a steady state where the current density is zero everywhere.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] where Δ*V* is the thermoelectric voltage seen at the terminals.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Note that the voltage shift expressed by the Seebeck effect cannot be measured directly, since the measured voltage (by attaching a voltmeter) contains an additional voltage contribution, due to the temperature gradient and Seebeck effect in the measurement leads.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The voltmeter voltage is always dependent on *relative* Seebeck coefficients among the various materials involved.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] where $\scriptstyle \mathbf {J}$ is the current density, $\scriptstyle \sigma$ is the electrical conductivity, $\scriptstyle {\boldsymbol {\nabla }}V$ is the voltage gradient, and $\scriptstyle {\boldsymbol {\nabla }}T$ is the temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Thus, if *S* is positive, the end with the higher temperature has the lower voltage, and vice versa.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The voltage gradient in the material will point against the temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Seebeck effect is generally dominated by the contribution from charge carrier diffusion (see below) which tends to push charge carriers towards the cold side of the material until a compensating voltage has built up.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] As a result, in p-type semiconductors (which have only positive mobile charges, electron holes), *S* is positive.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Likewise, in n-type semiconductors (which have only negative mobile charges, electrons), *S* is negative.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In most conductors, however, the charge carriers exhibit both hole-like and electron-like behaviour and the sign of *S* usually depends on which of them predominates.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] where T is the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The constant of integration is such that $\scriptstyle S=0$ at absolute zero, as required by Nernst's theorem.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In practice the absolute Seebeck coefficient is difficult to measure directly, since the voltage output of a thermoelectric circuit, as measured by a voltmeter, only depends on *differences* of Seebeck coefficients.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This is because electrodes attached to a voltmeter must be placed onto the material in order to measure the thermoelectric voltage.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The temperature gradient then also typically induces a thermoelectric voltage across one leg of the measurement electrodes.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Therefore, the measured Seebeck coefficient is a contribution from the Seebeck coefficient of the material of interest and the material of the measurement electrodes.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This arrangement of two materials is usually called a thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Although only relative Seebeck coefficients are important for externally measured voltages, the absolute Seebeck coefficient can be important for other effects where voltage is measured indirectly.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Determination of the absolute Seebeck coefficient therefore requires more complicated techniques and is more difficult, but such measurements have been performed on standard materials.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In principle these measurements only have to be performed once for all time, and for all materials; for any other material, the absolute Seebeck coefficient can be obtained by performing a relative Seebeck coefficient measurement against another material with known absolute value.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The reason this works is that $S(T)$ is expected to decrease to zero as the temperature is brought to zero—a consequence of Nernst's theorem.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Such a measurement based on the integration of ${\mathcal {K}}/T$ was published in 1932, though it relied on the interpolation of the Thomson coefficient in certain regions of temperature.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Superconductors have zero Seebeck coefficient, as mentioned below.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] By making one of the wires in a thermocouple superconducting, it is possible to get a direct measurement of the absolute Seebeck coefficient of the other wire, since it alone determines the measured voltage from the entire thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] A publication in 1958 used this technique to measure the absolute Seebeck coefficient of lead between 7.2 K and 18 K, thereby filling in an important gap in the previous 1932 experiment mentioned above.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The combination of the superconductor-thermocouple technique up to 18 K, with the Thomson-coefficient-integration technique above 18 K, allowed determination of the absolute Seebeck coefficient of lead up to room temperature.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] By proxy, these measurements led to the determination of absolute Seebeck coefficients for *all materials*, even up to higher temperatures, by a combination of Thomson coefficient integrations and thermocouple circuits.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The difficulty of these measurements, and the rarity of reproducing experiments, lends some degree of uncertainty to the absolute thermoelectric scale thus obtained.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In particular, the 1932 measurements may have incorrectly measured the Thomson coefficient over the range 20 K to 50 K.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Since nearly all subsequent publications relied on those measurements, this would mean that all of the commonly used values of absolute Seebeck coefficient (including those shown in the figures) are too low by about 0.3 μV/K, for all temperatures above 50 K.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In the table below are Seebeck coefficients at room temperature for some common, nonexotic materials, measured relative to platinum.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Seebeck coefficient of platinum itself is approximately −5 μV/K at room temperature, and so the values listed below should be compensated accordingly.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] For example, the Seebeck coefficients of Cu, Ag, Au are 1.5 μV/K, and of Al −1.5 μV/K.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Seebeck coefficient of semiconductors very much depends on doping, with generally positive values for p doped materials and negative values for n doping.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] A material's temperature, crystal structure, and impurities influence the value of thermoelectric coefficients.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Seebeck effect can be attributed to two things: charge-carrier diffusion and phonon drag.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In other words, the direction of the current in Ohm's law is determined via the thermodynamic arrow of time (the difference in chemical potential could be exploited to produce work, but is instead dissipated as heat which increases entropy).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] On the other hand, for the Seebeck effect not even the sign of the current can be predicted from thermodynamics, and so to understand the origin of the Seebeck coefficient it is necessary to understand the *microscopic* physics.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Charge carriers (such as thermally excited electrons) constantly diffuse around inside a conductive material.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Due to thermal fluctuations, some of these charge carriers travel with a higher energy than average, and some with a lower energy.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] When no voltage differences or temperature differences are applied, the carrier diffusion perfectly balances out and so on average one sees no current: $\scriptstyle \mathbf {J} =0$ .
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] A net current can be generated by applying a voltage difference (Ohm's law), or by applying a temperature difference (Seebeck effect).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] To understand the microscopic origin of the thermoelectric effect, it is useful to first describe the microscopic mechanism of the normal Ohm's law electrical conductance—to describe what determines the $\scriptstyle \sigma$ in $\scriptstyle \mathbf {J} =-\sigma {\boldsymbol {\nabla }}V$ .
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Microscopically, what is happening in Ohm's law is that higher energy levels have a higher concentration of carriers per state, on the side with higher chemical potential.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] For each interval of energy, the carriers tend to diffuse and spread into the area of device where there are fewer carriers per state of that energy.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] As they move, however, they occasionally scatter dissipatively, which re-randomizes their energy according to the local temperature and chemical potential.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This dissipation empties out the carriers from these higher energy states, allowing more to diffuse in.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The combination of diffusion and dissipation favours an overall drift of the charge carriers towards the side of the material where they have a lower chemical potential.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] For the thermoelectric effect, now, consider the case of uniform voltage (uniform chemical potential) with a temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In this case, at the hotter side of the material there is more variation in the energies of the charge carriers, compared to the colder side.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This means that high energy levels have a higher carrier occupation per state on the hotter side, but also the hotter side has a *lower* occupation per state at lower energy levels.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] As before, the high-energy carriers diffuse away from the hot end, and produce entropy by drifting towards the cold end of the device.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] However, there is a competing process: at the same time low-energy carriers are drawn back towards the hot end of the device.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Though these processes both generate entropy, they work against each other in terms of charge current, and so a net current only occurs if one of these drifts is stronger than the other.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The net current is given by $\scriptstyle \mathbf {J} =-\sigma S{\boldsymbol {\nabla }}T$ , where (as shown below) the thermoelectric coefficient $\scriptstyle \sigma S$ depends literally on how conductive high-energy carriers are, compared to low-energy carriers.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The distinction may be due to a difference in rate of scattering, a difference in speeds, a difference in density of states, or a combination of these effects.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The processes described above apply in materials where each charge carrier sees an essentially static environment so that its motion can be described independently from other carriers, and independent of other dynamics (such as phonons).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] where $\scriptstyle c(E)$ is the energy-dependent conductivity, and $\scriptstyle f(E)$ is the Fermi–Dirac distribution function.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] These equations are known as the Mott relations, of Sir Nevill Francis Mott.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] is a function peaked around the chemical potential (Fermi level) $\mu$ with a width of approximately $3.5k_{\rm {B}}T$ .
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In materials with strong interactions, none of the above equations can be used since it is not possible to consider each charge carrier as a separate entity.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Wiedemann–Franz law can also be exactly derived using the non-interacting electron picture, and so in materials where the Wiedemann–Franz law fails (such as superconductors), the Mott relations also generally tend to fail.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This expression is sometimes called "the Mott formula", however it is much less general than Mott's original formula expressed above.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In highly conductive metals the Fermi temperatures are typically around 104 – 105 K, and so it is understandable why their absolute Seebeck coefficients are only of order 1 – 10 μV/K at room temperature.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Note that whereas the free electron model predicts a negative Seebeck coefficient, real metals actually have complicated band structures and may exhibit positive Seebeck coefficients (examples: Cu, Ag, Au).
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The fraction $\scriptstyle c'(\mu )/c(\mu )$ in semimetals is sometimes calculated from the measured derivative of $\scriptstyle \sigma _{\rm {metal}}$ with respect to some energy shift induced by field effect.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This is not necessarily correct and the estimate of $\scriptstyle c'(\mu )/c(\mu )$ can be incorrect (by a factor of two or more), since the disorder potential depends on screening which also changes with field effect.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In semiconductors at low levels of doping, transport only occurs far away from the Fermi level.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] At low doping in the conduction band (where $\scriptstyle E_{\rm {C}}-\mu \gg k_{\rm {B}}T$ , where $\scriptstyle E_{\rm {C}}$ is the minimum energy of the conduction band edge), one has $\scriptstyle -{\frac {df(E)}{dE}}\approx {\tfrac {1}{k_{\rm {B}}T}}e^{-(E-\mu )/(k_{\rm {B}}T)}$ .
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The values of $\scriptstyle a_{\rm {C}}$ and $\scriptstyle a_{\rm {V}}$ depend on material details; in bulk semiconductor these constants range between 1 and 3, the extremes corresponding to acoustic-mode lattice scattering and ionized-impurity scattering.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] In extrinsic (doped) semiconductors either the conduction or valence band will dominate transport, and so one of the numbers above will give the measured values.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This results in a crossover behaviour, as shown in the figure.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The highest Seebeck coefficient is obtained when the semiconductor is lightly doped, however a high Seebeck coefficient is not necessarily useful on its own.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] For thermoelectric power devices (coolers, generators) it is more important to maximize the thermoelectric power factor $\scriptstyle \sigma S^{2}$ , or the thermoelectric figure of merit, and the optimum generally occurs at high doping levels.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Phonons are not always in local thermal equilibrium; they move against the thermal gradient.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] They lose momentum by interacting with electrons (or other carriers) and imperfections in the crystal.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] If the phonon-electron interaction is predominant, the phonons will tend to push the electrons to one end of the material, hence losing momentum and contributing to the thermoelectric field.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This contribution is most important in the temperature region where phonon-electron scattering is predominant.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] where $\scriptstyle \theta _{\rm {D}}$ is the Debye temperature.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] At lower temperatures there are fewer phonons available for drag, and at higher temperatures they tend to lose momentum in phonon-phonon scattering instead of phonon-electron scattering.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] At lower temperatures, material boundaries also play an increasing role as the phonons can travel significant distances.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] Practically speaking, phonon drag is an important effect in semiconductors near room temperature (even though well above $\scriptstyle \theta _{\rm {D}}/5$ ), that is comparable in magnitude to the carrier-diffusion effect described in the previous section.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] This region of the thermopower-versus-temperature function is highly variable under a magnetic field.
[src:thermocouples/seebeck-coefficient] The Seebeck coefficient of a material corresponds thermodynamically to the amount of entropy "dragged along" by the flow of charge inside a material; it is in some sense the entropy per unit charge in the material.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A **thermocouple**, also known as a **thermoelectrical thermometer**, is an electrical device consisting of two dissimilar electrical conductors forming an electrical junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A thermocouple produces a temperature-dependent voltage as a result of the Seebeck effect, and this voltage can be interpreted to measure temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples are widely used as temperature sensors.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Commercial thermocouples are inexpensive, interchangeable, are supplied with standard connectors, and can measure a wide range of temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In contrast to most other methods of temperature measurement, thermocouples are self-powered and require no external form of excitation.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The main limitation with thermocouples is accuracy; system errors of less than one degree Celsius (°C) can be difficult to achieve.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples are widely used in science and industry.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Applications include temperature measurement for kilns, gas turbine exhaust, diesel engines, and other industrial processes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples are also used in homes, offices and businesses as the temperature sensors in thermostats, and also as flame sensors in safety devices for gas-powered appliances.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In 1821, the German physicist Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a magnetic needle held near a circuit made up of two dissimilar metals got deflected when one of the dissimilar metal junctions was heated.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] At the time, Seebeck referred to this consequence as thermo-magnetism.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The magnetic field he observed was later shown to be due to thermo-electric current.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In practical use, the voltage generated at a single junction of two different types of wire is what is of interest as this can be used to measure temperature at very high and low temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The magnitude of the voltage depends on the types of wire being used.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Generally, the voltage is in the microvolt range and care must be taken to obtain a usable measurement.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Although very little current flows, power can be generated by a single thermocouple junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Power generation using multiple thermocouples, as in a thermopile, is common.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The standard configuration of a thermocouple is shown in the figure.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The dissimilar conductors contact at the measuring (aka hot) junction and at the reference (aka cold) junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The thermocouple is connected to the electrical system at its reference junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The figure shows the measuring junction on the left, the reference junction in the middle and represents the rest of the electrical system as a voltage meter on the right.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The temperature *T*sense is obtained via a characteristic function *E*(*T*) for the type of thermocouple which requires inputs: measured voltage *V* and reference junction temperature *T*ref.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The solution to the equation *E*(*T*sense) = *V* + *E*(*T*ref) yields *T*sense.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Sometimes these details are hidden inside a device that packages the reference junction block (with *T*ref thermometer), voltmeter, and equation solver.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The Seebeck effect refers to the development of an electromotive force across two points of an electrically conducting material when there is a temperature difference between those two points.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] where $S(T)$ is a temperature-dependent material property known as the Seebeck coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Change from $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ to $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {sense} }$ , in the alumel wire.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Change from $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {sense} }$ to $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ , in the chromel wire.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Change from $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ to $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {meter} }$ , in the upper copper wire.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The first and fourth contributions cancel out exactly, because these regions involve the same temperature change and an identical material.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] As a result, $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {meter} }$ does not influence the measured voltage.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The second and third contributions do not cancel, as they involve different materials.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] where $\scriptstyle S_{+}$ and $\scriptstyle S_{-}$ are the Seebeck coefficients of the conductors attached to the positive and negative terminals of the voltmeter, respectively (chromel and alumel in the figure).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The constant of integration in this indefinite integral has no significance, but is conventionally chosen such that $\scriptstyle E(0\,{}^{\circ }{\rm {C}})=0$ .
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouple manufacturers and metrology standards organizations such as NIST provide tables of the function $\scriptstyle E(T)$ that have been measured and interpolated over a range of temperatures, for particular thermocouple types (see *External links* section for access to these tables).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] To obtain the desired measurement of $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {sense} }$ , it is not sufficient to just measure $\scriptstyle V$ .
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The temperature at the reference junctions $\scriptstyle T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ must also be known.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In both cases the value $\scriptstyle V+E(T_{\mathrm {ref} })$ is calculated, then the function $\scriptstyle E(T)$ is searched for a matching value.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples ideally should be very simple measurement devices, with each type being characterized by a precise $\scriptstyle E(T)$ curve, independent of any other details.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In reality, thermocouples are affected by issues such as alloy manufacturing uncertainties, aging effects, and circuit design mistakes/misunderstandings.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A common error in thermocouple construction is related to cold junction compensation.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If an error is made on the estimation of $T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ , an error will appear in the temperature measurement.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For the simplest measurements, thermocouple wires are connected to copper far away from the hot or cold point whose temperature is measured; this reference junction is then assumed to be at room temperature, but that temperature can vary.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Because of the nonlinearity in the thermocouple voltage curve, the errors in $T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {sense} }$ are generally unequal values.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Some thermocouples, such as Type B, have a relatively flat voltage curve near room temperature, meaning that a large uncertainty in a room-temperature $T_{\mathrm {ref} }$ translates to only a small error in $T_{\mathrm {sense} }$ .
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Junctions should be made in a reliable manner, but there are many possible approaches to accomplish this.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For low temperatures, junctions can be brazed or soldered; however, it may be difficult to find a suitable flux and this may not be suitable at the sensing junction due to the solder's low melting point.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Reference and extension junctions are therefore usually made with screw terminal blocks.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For high temperatures, the most common approach is the spot weld or crimp using a durable material.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] One common myth regarding thermocouples is that junctions must be made cleanly without involving a third metal, to avoid unwanted added EMFs.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This may result from another common misunderstanding that the voltage is generated at the junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In fact, the junctions should in principle have uniform internal temperature; therefore, no voltage is generated at the junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The voltage is generated in the thermal gradient, along the wire.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A thermocouple produces small signals, often microvolts in magnitude.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Precise measurements of this signal require an amplifier with low input offset voltage and with care taken to avoid thermal EMFs from self-heating within the voltmeter itself.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If the thermocouple wire has a high resistance for some reason (poor contact at junctions, or very thin wires used for fast thermal response), the measuring instrument should have high input impedance to prevent an offset in the measured voltage.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A useful feature in thermocouple instrumentation will simultaneously measure resistance and detect faulty connections in the wiring or at thermocouple junctions.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] While a thermocouple wire type is often described by its chemical composition, the actual aim is to produce a pair of wires that follow a standardized $\scriptstyle E(T)$ curve.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Impurities affect each batch of metal differently, producing variable Seebeck coefficients.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] To match the standard behaviour, thermocouple wire manufacturers will deliberately mix in additional impurities to "dope" the alloy, compensating for uncontrolled variations in source material.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] As a result, there are standard and specialized grades of thermocouple wire, depending on the level of precision demanded in the thermocouple behaviour.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Precision grades may only be available in matched pairs, where one wire is modified to compensate for deficiencies in the other wire.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A special case of thermocouple wire is known as "extension grade", designed to carry the thermoelectric circuit over a longer distance.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Extension wires follow the stated $\scriptstyle E(T)$ curve but for various reasons they are not designed to be used in extreme environments and so they cannot be used at the sensing junction in some applications.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example, an extension wire may be in a different form, such as highly flexible with stranded construction and plastic insulation, or be part of a multi-wire cable for carrying many thermocouple circuits.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] With expensive noble metal thermocouples, the extension wires may even be made of a completely different, cheaper material that mimics the standard type over a reduced temperature range.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples are often used at high temperatures and in reactive furnace atmospheres.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In this case, the practical lifetime is limited by thermocouple aging.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The thermoelectric coefficients of the wires in a thermocouple that is used to measure very high temperatures may change with time, and the measurement voltage accordingly drops.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The simple relationship between the temperature difference of the junctions and the measurement voltage is only correct if each wire is homogeneous (uniform in composition).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] As thermocouples age in a process, their conductors can lose homogeneity due to chemical and metallurgical changes caused by extreme or prolonged exposure to high temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If the aged section of the thermocouple circuit is exposed to a temperature gradient, the measured voltage will differ, resulting in error.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Aged thermocouples are only partly modified; for example, being unaffected in the parts outside the furnace.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For this reason, aged thermocouples cannot be taken out of their installed location and recalibrated in a bath or test furnace to determine error.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Likewise, an aged thermocouple that is pushed deeper into the furnace might sometimes provide a more accurate reading if being pushed further into the furnace causes the temperature gradient to occur only in a fresh section.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Certain combinations of alloys have become popular as industry standards.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Selection of the combination is driven by cost, availability, convenience, melting point, chemical properties, stability, and output.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Different types are best suited for different applications.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They are usually selected on the basis of the temperature range and sensitivity needed.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples with low sensitivities (B, R, and S types) have correspondingly lower resolutions.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Other selection criteria include the chemical inertness of the thermocouple material and whether it is magnetic or not.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Standard thermocouple types are listed below with the positive electrode (assuming $T_{\text{sense}}>T_{\text{ref}}$ ) first, followed by the negative electrode.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type E (chromel–constantan) has a high output (68 μV/°C), which makes it well suited to cryogenic use.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type J (iron–constantan) has a more restricted range (−40 °C to +1200 °C) than type K but higher sensitivity of about 50 μV/°C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The Curie point of the iron (770 °C) causes a smooth change in the characteristic, which determines the upper-temperature limit.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Note, the European/German Type L is a variant of the type J, with a different specification for the EMF output (reference DIN 43712:1985-01).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The positive wire is made of hard iron, while the negative wire consists of softer copper-nickel.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Due to its iron content, the J-type is slightly heavier and the positive wire is magnetic.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] It is highly vulnerable to corrosion in reducing atmospheres, which can lead to significant degradation of the thermocouple's performance.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type K (chromel–alumel) is the most common general-purpose thermocouple with a sensitivity of approximately 41 μV/°C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] It is inexpensive, and a wide variety of probes are available in its −200 °C to +1350 °C (−330 °F to +2460 °F) range.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type K was specified at a time when metallurgy was less advanced than it is today, and consequently characteristics may vary considerably between samples.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] One of the constituent metals, nickel, is magnetic; a characteristic of thermocouples made with magnetic material is that they undergo a deviation in output when the material reaches its Curie point, which occurs for type K thermocouples at around 150 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They operate very well in oxidizing atmospheres.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If, however, a mostly reducing atmosphere (such as hydrogen with a small amount of oxygen) comes into contact with the wires, the chromium in the chromel alloy oxidizes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This reduces the EMF output, and the thermocouple reads low.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This phenomenon is known as *green rot*, due to the color of the affected alloy.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Although not always distinctively green, the chromel wire will develop a mottled silvery skin and become magnetic.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] An easy way to check for this problem is to see whether the two wires are magnetic (normally, chromel is non-magnetic).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Hydrogen in the atmosphere is the usual cause of green rot.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] At high temperatures, it can diffuse through solid metals or an intact metal thermowell.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Even a sheath of magnesium oxide insulating the thermocouple will not keep the hydrogen out.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Green rot does not occur in atmospheres sufficiently rich in oxygen, or oxygen-free.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A sealed thermowell can be filled with inert gas, or an oxygen scavenger (e.g. a sacrificial titanium wire) can be added.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Alternatively, additional oxygen can be introduced into the thermowell.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Another option is using a different thermocouple type for the low-oxygen atmospheres where green rot can occur; a type N thermocouple is a suitable alternative.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type M (82%Ni/18%Mo–99.2%Ni/0.8%Co, by weight) are used in vacuum furnaces for the same reasons as with type C (described below).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Upper temperature is limited to 1400 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] It is less commonly used than other types.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type N (Nicrosil–Nisil) thermocouples are suitable for use between −270 °C and +1300 °C, owing to its stability and oxidation resistance.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Sensitivity is about 39 μV/°C at 900 °C, slightly lower compared to type K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Designed at the Defence Science and Technology Organisation (DSTO) of Australia, by Noel A.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A short-term cyclic change in thermal EMF on heating in the temperature range about 250–650 °C, which occurs in thermocouples of types K, J, T, and E.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This kind of EMF instability is associated with structural changes such as magnetic short-range order in the metallurgical composition.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A time-independent perturbation in thermal EMF in specific temperature ranges.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This is due to composition-dependent magnetic transformations that perturb the thermal EMFs in type-K thermocouples in the range about 25–225 °C, and in type J above 730 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The Nicrosil and Nisil thermocouple alloys show greatly enhanced thermoelectric stability relative to the other standard base-metal thermocouple alloys because their compositions substantially reduce the thermoelectric instabilities described above.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type N thermocouples are suitable alternative to type K for low-oxygen conditions where type K is prone to green rot.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They are suitable for use in vacuum, inert atmospheres, oxidizing atmospheres, or dry reducing atmospheres.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They do not tolerate the presence of sulfur.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type T (copper–constantan) thermocouples are suited for measurements in the −200 to 350 °C range.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Often used as a differential measurement, since only copper wire touches the probes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Since both conductors are non-magnetic, there is no Curie point and thus no abrupt change in characteristics.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type-T thermocouples have a sensitivity of about 43 μV/°C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Note that copper has a much higher thermal conductivity than the alloys generally used in thermocouple constructions, and so it is necessary to exercise extra care with thermally anchoring type-T thermocouples.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A similar composition is found in the obsolete Type U in the German specification DIN 43712:1985-01.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Types B, R, and S thermocouples use platinum or a platinum/rhodium alloy for each conductor.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] These are among the most stable thermocouples, but have lower sensitivity than other types, approximately 10 μV/°C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type B, R, and S thermocouples are usually used only for high-temperature measurements due to their high cost and low sensitivity.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For type R and S thermocouples, HTX platinum wire can be used in place of the pure platinum leg to strengthen the thermocouple and prevent failures from grain growth that can occur in high temperature and harsh conditions.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type B (70%Pt/30%Rh–94%Pt/6%Rh, by weight) thermocouples are suited for use at up to 1800 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type-B thermocouples produce the same output at 0 °C and 42 °C, limiting their use below about 50 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The EMF function has a minimum around 21 °C (for 21.020262 °C EMF=-2.584972 μV), meaning that cold-junction compensation is easily performed, since the compensation voltage is essentially a constant for a reference at typical room temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type R (87%Pt/13%Rh–Pt, by weight) thermocouples are used 0 to 1600 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type R Thermocouples are quite stable and capable of long operating life when used in clean, favorable conditions.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] When used above 1100 °C ( 2000 °F), these thermocouples must be protected from exposure to metallic and non-metallic vapors.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type R is not suitable for direct insertion into metallic protecting tubes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Long term high temperature exposure causes grain growth which can lead to mechanical failure and a negative calibration drift caused by Rhodium diffusion to pure platinum leg as well as from Rhodium volatilization.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This type has the same uses as type S, but is not interchangeable with it.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type S (90%Pt/10%Rh–Pt, by weight) thermocouples, similar to type R, are used up to 1600 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Before the introduction of the International Temperature Scale of 1990 (ITS-90), precision type-S thermocouples were used as the practical standard thermometers for the range of 630 °C to 1064 °C, based on an interpolation between the freezing points of antimony, silver, and gold.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Starting with ITS-90, platinum resistance thermometers have taken over this range as standard thermometers.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] These thermocouples are well-suited for measuring extremely high temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Typical uses are hydrogen and inert atmospheres, as well as vacuum furnaces.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They are not used in oxidizing environments at high temperatures because of embrittlement.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A typical range is 0 to 2315 °C, which can be extended to 2760 °C in inert atmosphere and to 3000 °C for brief measurements.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Pure tungsten at high temperatures undergoes recrystallization and becomes brittle.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Therefore, types C and D are preferred over type G in some applications.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In presence of water vapor at high temperature, tungsten reacts to form tungsten(VI) oxide, which volatilizes away, and hydrogen.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Hydrogen then reacts with tungsten oxide, after which water is formed again.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Such a "water cycle" can lead to erosion of the thermocouple and eventual failure.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In high temperature vacuum applications, it is therefore desirable to avoid the presence of traces of water.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] An alternative to tungsten/rhenium is tungsten/molybdenum, but the voltage–temperature response is weaker and has minimum at around 1000 K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The thermocouple temperature is limited also by other materials used.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example beryllium oxide, a popular material for high temperature applications, tends to gain conductivity with temperature; a particular configuration of sensor had the insulation resistance dropping from a megaohm at 1000 K to 200 ohms at 2200 K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] At high temperatures, the materials undergo chemical reaction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] At 2700 K beryllium oxide slightly reacts with tungsten, tungsten-rhenium alloy, and tantalum; at 2600 K molybdenum reacts with BeO, tungsten does not react.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] BeO begins melting at about 2820 K, magnesium oxide at about 3020 K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] (95%W/5%Re–74%W/26%Re, by weight) maximum temperature will be measured by type-c thermocouple is 2329 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In these thermocouples (chromel–gold/iron alloy), the negative wire is gold with a small fraction (0.03–0.15 atom percent) of iron.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The impure gold wire gives the thermocouple a high sensitivity at low temperatures (compared to other thermocouples at that temperature), whereas the chromel wire maintains the sensitivity near room temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] It can be used for cryogenic applications (1.2–300 K and even up to 600 K).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Both the sensitivity and the temperature range depend on the iron concentration.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The sensitivity is typically around 15 μV/K at low temperatures, and the lowest usable temperature varies between 1.2 and 4.2 K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Platinel II (55%Pd/31%Pt/14%Au–65%Au/35%Pd) thermocouples have a temperature-voltage transfer function that mimics that of type K.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The advantage is that the noble metal alloys used are resistant to high temperature oxidizing gases.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This combination was developed by Engelhard.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples of platinum/molybdenum-alloy (95%Pt/5%Mo–99.9%Pt/0.1%Mo, by weight) are sometimes used in nuclear reactors, since they show a low drift from nuclear transmutation induced by neutron irradiation, compared to the platinum/rhodium-alloy types.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The use of two wires of iridium/rhodium alloys can provide a thermocouple that can be used up to about 2000 °C in inert atmospheres.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples made from two different, high-purity noble metals can show high accuracy even when uncalibrated, as well as low levels of drift.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Two combinations in use are gold–platinum and platinum–palladium.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Their main limitations are the low melting points of the metals involved (1064 °C for gold and 1555 °C for palladium).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] These thermocouples tend to be more accurate than type S, and due to their economy and simplicity are even regarded as competitive alternatives to the platinum resistance thermometers that are normally used as standard thermometers.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] HTIR-TC offers a breakthrough in measuring high-temperature processes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Its characteristics are: durable and reliable at high temperatures, up to at least 1700 °C; resistant to irradiation; moderately priced; available in a variety of configurations - adaptable to each application; easily installed.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Originally developed for use in nuclear test reactors, HTIR-TC may enhance the safety of operations in future reactors.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This thermocouple was developed by researchers at the Idaho National Laboratory (INL).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The table below describes properties of several different thermocouple types.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Within the tolerance columns, *T* represents the temperature of the hot junction, in degrees Celsius.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example, a thermocouple with a tolerance of ±0.0025×*T* would have a tolerance of ±2.5 °C at 1000 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Each cell in the Color Code columns depicts the end of a thermocouple cable, showing the jacket color and the color of the individual leads.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The background color represents the color of the connector body.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Each sensor needs individual calibration.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The wires that make up the thermocouple must be insulated from each other everywhere, except at the sensing junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Any additional electrical contact between the wires, or contact of a wire to other conductive objects, can modify the voltage and give a false reading of temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Plastics are suitable insulators for low temperatures parts of a thermocouple, whereas ceramic insulation can be used up to around 1000 °C.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Other concerns (abrasion and chemical resistance) also affect the suitability of materials.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] When wire insulation disintegrates, it can result in an unintended electrical contact at a different location from the desired sensing point.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If such a damaged thermocouple is used in the closed loop control of a thermostat or other temperature controller, this can lead to a runaway overheating event and possibly severe damage, as the false temperature reading will typically be lower than the sensing junction temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Failed insulation will also typically outgas, which can lead to process contamination.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For parts of thermocouples used at very high temperatures or in contamination-sensitive applications, the only suitable insulation may be vacuum or inert gas; the mechanical rigidity of the thermocouple wires is used to keep them separated.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Temperature ratings for insulations may vary based on what the overall thermocouple construction cable consists of.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Note: T300 is a new high-temperature material that was recently approved by UL for 300 °C operating temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples are suitable for measuring over a large temperature range, from −270 up to 3000 °C (for a short time, in inert atmosphere).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Applications include temperature measurement for kilns, gas turbine exhaust, diesel engines, other industrial processes and fog machines.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] They are less suitable for applications where smaller temperature differences need to be measured with high accuracy, for example the range 0–100 °C with 0.1 °C accuracy.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For such applications thermistors, silicon bandgap temperature sensors and resistance thermometers are more suitable.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Type B, S, R and K thermocouples are used extensively in the steel and iron industries to monitor temperatures and chemistry throughout the steel making process.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Disposable, immersible, type S thermocouples are regularly used in the electric arc furnace process to accurately measure the temperature of steel before tapping.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The cooling curve of a small steel sample can be analyzed and used to estimate the carbon content of molten steel.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Many gas-fed heating appliances such as ovens and water heaters make use of a pilot flame to ignite the main gas burner when required.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If the pilot flame goes out, unburned gas may be released, which is an explosion risk and a health hazard.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] To prevent this, some appliances use a thermocouple in a fail-safe circuit to sense when the pilot light is burning.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The tip of the thermocouple is placed in the pilot flame, generating a voltage which operates the supply valve which feeds gas to the pilot.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] So long as the pilot flame remains lit, the thermocouple remains hot, and the pilot gas valve is held open.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] If the pilot light goes out, the thermocouple temperature falls, causing the voltage across the thermocouple to drop and the valve to close.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Where the probe may be easily placed above the flame, a rectifying sensor may often be used instead.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] With part ceramic construction, they may also be known as flame rods, flame sensors or flame detection electrodes.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] These systems are identifiable by the "press and hold for x minutes" in the pilot lighting instructions.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Apart from testing the open circuit voltage of the thermocouple, and the near short-circuit DC continuity through the thermocouple gas valve coil, the easiest non-specialist test is substitution of a known good gas valve.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Some systems, known as millivolt control systems, extend the thermocouple concept to both open and close the main gas valve as well.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Not only does the voltage created by the pilot thermocouple activate the pilot gas valve, it is also routed through a thermostat to power the main gas valve as well.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Here, a larger voltage is needed than in a pilot flame safety system described above, and a thermopile is used rather than a single thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Such a system requires no external source of electricity for its operation and thus can operate during a power failure, provided that all the other related system components allow for this.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] This excludes common forced air furnaces because external electrical power is required to operate the blower motor, but this feature is especially useful for un-powered convection heaters.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A similar gas shut-off safety mechanism using a thermocouple is sometimes employed to ensure that the main burner ignites within a certain time period, shutting off the main burner gas supply valve should that not happen.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Out of concern about energy wasted by the standing pilot flame, designers of many newer appliances have switched to an electronically controlled pilot-less ignition, also called intermittent ignition.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] With no standing pilot flame, there is no risk of gas buildup should the flame go out, so these appliances do not need thermocouple-based pilot safety switches.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] As these designs lose the benefit of operation without a continuous source of electricity, standing pilots are still used in some appliances.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The exception is later model instantaneous (aka "tankless") water heaters that use the flow of water to generate the current required to ignite the gas burner; these designs also use a thermocouple as a safety cut-off device in the event the gas fails to ignite, or if the flame is extinguished.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermopiles are used for measuring the intensity of incident radiation, typically visible or infrared light, which heats the hot junctions, while the cold junctions are on a heat sink.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] It is possible to measure radiative intensities of only a few μW/cm2 with commercially available thermopile sensors.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example, some laser power meters are based on such sensors; these are specifically known as thermopile laser sensor.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The principle of operation of a thermopile sensor is distinct from that of a bolometer, as the latter relies on a change in resistance.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples can generally be used in the testing of prototype electrical and mechanical apparatus.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example, switchgear under test for its current carrying capacity may have thermocouples installed and monitored during a heat run test, to confirm that the temperature rise at rated current does not exceed designed limits.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A thermocouple can produce current to drive some processes directly, without the need for extra circuitry and power sources.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For example, the power from a thermocouple can activate a valve when a temperature difference arises.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The electrical energy generated by a thermocouple is converted from the heat which must be supplied to the hot side to maintain the electric potential.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A continuous transfer of heat is necessary because the current flowing through the thermocouple tends to cause the hot side to cool down and the cold side to heat up (the Peltier effect).
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermocouples can be connected in series to form a thermopile, where all the hot junctions are exposed to a higher temperature and all the cold junctions to a lower temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The output is the sum of the voltages across the individual junctions, giving larger voltage and power output.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In a radioisotope thermoelectric generator, the radioactive decay of transuranic elements as a heat source has been used to power spacecraft on missions too far from the Sun to use solar power.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Thermopiles heated by kerosene lamps were used to run batteryless radio receivers in isolated areas.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] There are commercially produced lanterns that use the heat from a candle to run several light-emitting diodes, and thermoelectrically powered fans to improve air circulation and heat distribution in wood stoves.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Chemical production and petroleum refineries will usually employ computers for logging and for limit testing the many temperatures associated with a process, typically numbering in the hundreds.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] For such cases, a number of thermocouple leads will be brought to a common reference block (a large block of copper) containing the second thermocouple of each circuit.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The temperature of the block is in turn measured by a thermistor.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] Simple computations are used to determine the temperature at each measured location.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] A thermocouple can be used as a vacuum gauge over the range of approximately 0.001 to 1 torr absolute pressure.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In this pressure range, the mean free path of the gas is comparable to the dimensions of the vacuum chamber, and the flow regime is neither purely viscous nor purely molecular.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] In this configuration, the thermocouple junction is attached to the centre of a short heating wire, which is usually energised by a constant current of about 5 mA, and the heat is removed at a rate related to the thermal conductivity of the gas.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The temperature detected at the thermocouple junction depends on the thermal conductivity of the surrounding gas, which depends on the pressure of the gas.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The potential difference measured by a thermocouple is proportional to the square of pressure over the low- to medium-vacuum range.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] At higher (viscous flow) and lower (molecular flow) pressures, the thermal conductivity of air or any other gas is essentially independent of pressure.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The thermocouple was first used as a vacuum gauge by Voege in 1906.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] where *P* is the gas pressure, *B* is a constant that depends on the thermocouple temperature, the gas composition and the vacuum-chamber geometry, *V*0 is the thermocouple voltage at zero pressure (absolute), and *V* is the voltage indicated by the thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/thermocouple] The alternative is the Pirani gauge, which operates in a similar way, over approximately the same pressure range, but is only a 2-terminal device, sensing the change in resistance with temperature of a thin electrically heated wire, rather than using a thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The **thermoelectric effect** is the direct conversion of temperature differences to electric voltage and vice versa via a thermocouple.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] A thermoelectric device creates a voltage when there is a different temperature on each side.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Conversely, when a voltage is applied to it, heat is transferred from one side to the other, creating a temperature difference.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This effect can be used to generate electricity, measure temperature or change the temperature of objects.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Because the direction of heating and cooling is affected by the applied voltage, thermoelectric devices can be used as temperature controllers.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Seebeck and Peltier effects are different manifestations of the same physical process; textbooks may refer to this process as the **Peltier–Seebeck effect** (the separation derives from the independent discoveries by Jean Charles Athanase Peltier and Thomas Johann Seebeck).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Thomson effect is an extension of the Peltier–Seebeck model and is credited to Lord Kelvin.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Joule heating, the heat that is generated whenever a current is passed through a conductive material, is not generally termed a thermoelectric effect.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Peltier–Seebeck and Thomson effects are thermodynamically reversible, whereas Joule heating is not.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] At the atomic scale, a temperature gradient causes charge carriers in the material to diffuse from the hot side to the cold side.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This is due to charge carrier particles having higher mean velocities (and thus kinetic energy) at higher temperatures, leading them to migrate on average towards the colder side, in the process carrying heat across the material.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Depending on the material properties and nature of the charge carriers (whether they are positive holes in a bulk material or electrons of negative charge), heat can be carried in either direction with respect to voltage.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Semiconductors of n-type and p-type are often combined in series as they have opposite directions for heat transport, as specified by the sign of their Seebeck coefficients.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The **Seebeck effect** is the emergence of electromotive force (EMF) that develops across two points of an electrically conducting material when there is a temperature difference between them.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The EMF is called the Seebeck EMF (or thermo/thermal/thermoelectric EMF).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The ratio between the EMF and temperature difference is the Seebeck coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] A thermocouple measures the difference in potential across a hot and cold end for two dissimilar materials.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This potential difference is proportional to the temperature difference between the hot and cold ends.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] First discovered in 1794 by Alessandro Volta, it is named after Thomas Johann Seebeck, who rediscovered it in 1821.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Seebeck observed what he called "thermomagnetic effect" wherein a magnetic compass needle would be deflected by a closed loop formed by two different metals joined in two places, with an applied temperature difference between the joints.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Hans Christian Ørsted noted that the temperature difference was in fact driving an electric current, with the generation of magnetic field being an indirect consequence, and so coined the more accurate term "thermoelectricity".
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Seebeck effect is a classic example of an electromotive force (EMF) and leads to measurable currents or voltages in the same way as any other EMF.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where V is the local voltage, and $\sigma$ is the local conductivity.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where S is the Seebeck coefficient (also known as thermopower), a property of the local material, and $\nabla T$ is the temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Seebeck coefficients generally vary as function of temperature and depend strongly on the composition of the conductor.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] For ordinary materials at room temperature, the Seebeck coefficient may range in value from −100 μV/K to +1,000 μV/K (see Seebeck coefficient article for more information).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] In practice, thermoelectric effects are essentially unobservable for a localized hot or cold spot in a single homogeneous conducting material, since the overall EMFs from the increasing and decreasing temperature gradients will perfectly cancel out.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Thermocouples involve two wires, each of a different material, that are electrically joined in a region of unknown temperature.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The loose ends are measured in an open-circuit state (without any current, $\mathbf {J} =0$ ).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Although the materials' Seebeck coefficients S are nonlinearly temperature dependent and different for the two materials, the open-circuit condition means that $\nabla V=-S\nabla T$ everywhere.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Therefore (see the thermocouple article for more details) the voltage measured at the loose ends of the wires is directly dependent on the unknown temperature, and yet totally independent of other details such as the exact geometry of the wires.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This direct relationship allows the thermocouple arrangement to be used as a straightforward uncalibrated thermometer, provided knowledge of the difference in S -vs- T curves of the two materials, and of the reference temperature at the measured loose wire ends.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This can help distinguish between different metals and alloys.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Thermopiles are formed from many thermocouples in series, zig-zagging back and forth between hot and cold.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Thermoelectric generators are like a thermocouple/thermopile but instead draw some current from the generated voltage in order to extract power from heat differentials.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] They are optimized differently from thermocouples, using high quality thermoelectric materials in a thermopile arrangement, to maximize the extracted power.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Though not particularly efficient, these generators have the advantage of not having any moving parts.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] When an electric current is passed through a circuit of a thermocouple, heat is generated (dumped, pumped) at one junction and absorbed at the other junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This is known as the **Peltier effect**: the presence of heating or cooling at an electrified junction of two different conductors.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The effect is named after French physicist Jean Charles Athanase Peltier, who discovered it in 1834.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] When a current is made to flow through a junction between two conductors, A and B, heat may be generated or removed at the junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where $\Pi _{\text{A}}$ and $\Pi _{\text{B}}$ are the Peltier coefficients of conductors A and B, and I is the electric current (from A to B).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The total heat generated is not determined by the Peltier effect alone, as it may also be influenced by Joule heating and thermal-gradient effects (see below).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Peltier coefficients represent how much heat is carried per unit charge.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Since charge current must be continuous across a junction, the associated heat flow will develop a discontinuity if $\Pi _{\text{A}}$ and $\Pi _{\text{B}}$ differ.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The close relationship between Peltier and Seebeck effects can be seen in the direct connection between their coefficients: $\Pi =TS$ (see below).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] A typical Peltier heat-pump involves multiple junctions in series, through which a current is driven.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Some of the junctions lose heat due to the Peltier effect, while others gain heat.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Thermoelectric heat pumps exploit this phenomenon, as do thermoelectric-cooling devices found in refrigerators.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] A **Peltier cell** operates on the basis of the Peltier effect.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Peltier effect can be used to create a heat pump.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Notably, the Peltier thermoelectric cooler is a refrigerator that is compact and has no circulating fluid or moving parts.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Such refrigerators are useful in applications where their advantages outweigh the disadvantage of their very low efficiency.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Other heat-pump applications such as dehumidifiers may also use Peltier heat-pumps.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Thermoelectric coolers are trivially reversible, in that they can be used as heaters by simply reversing the current.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Unlike ordinary resistive electrical heating (Joule heating) that varies with the square of current, the thermoelectric heating effect is linear in current (at least for small currents) but requires a cold sink to replenish with heat energy.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This rapid reversing heating and cooling effect is used by many modern thermal cyclers, laboratory devices used to amplify DNA by the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] PCR requires the cyclic heating and cooling of samples to specified temperatures.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The inclusion of many thermocouples in a small space enables many samples to be amplified in parallel.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] For certain materials, the Seebeck coefficient is not constant in temperature, and so a spatial gradient in temperature can result in a gradient in the Seebeck coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] If a current is driven through this gradient, then a continuous version of the Peltier effect will occur.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This **Thomson effect** was predicted and later observed in 1851 by Lord Kelvin (William Thomson).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] It describes the heating or cooling of a current-carrying conductor with a temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] If a current density $\mathbf {J}$ is passed through a homogeneous conductor, the Thomson effect predicts a heat production rate per unit volume.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where $\nabla T$ is the temperature gradient, and ${\mathcal {K}}$ is the Thomson coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Thomson effect is a manifestation of the direction of flow of electrical carriers with respect to a temperature gradient within a conductor.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] These absorb energy (heat) flowing in a direction opposite to a thermal gradient, increasing their potential energy, and, when flowing in the same direction as a thermal gradient, they liberate heat, decreasing their potential energy.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Thomson coefficient is related to the Seebeck coefficient as ${\mathcal {K}}=T{\tfrac {dS}{dT}}$ (see below).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This equation, however, neglects Joule heating and ordinary thermal conductivity (see full equations below).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Often, more than one of the above effects is involved in the operation of a real thermoelectric device.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Seebeck effect, Peltier effect, and Thomson effect can be gathered together in a consistent and rigorous way, described here; this also includes the effects of Joule heating and ordinary heat conduction.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] To describe the Peltier and Thomson effects, we must consider the flow of energy.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where $\kappa$ is the thermal conductivity.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The first term is the Fourier's heat conduction law, and the second term shows the energy carried by currents.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The third term, ${\dot {q}}_{\text{ext}}$ , is the heat added from an external source (if applicable).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] If the material has reached a steady state, the charge and temperature distributions are stable, so ${\dot {e}}=0$ and $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =0$ .
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The middle term is the Joule heating, and the last term includes both Peltier ( $\nabla S$ at junction) and Thomson ( $\nabla S$ in thermal gradient) effects.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] Combined with the Seebeck equation for $\mathbf {J}$ , this can be used to solve for the steady-state voltage and temperature profiles in a complicated system.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] If the material is not in a steady state, a complete description needs to include dynamic effects such as relating to electrical capacitance, inductance and heat capacity.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The thermoelectric effects lie beyond the scope of equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] They necessarily involve continuing flows of energy.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] At least, they involve three bodies or thermodynamic subsystems, arranged in a particular way, along with a special arrangement of the surroundings.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The three bodies are the two different metals and their junction region.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The junction region is an inhomogeneous body, assumed to be stable, not suffering amalgamation by diffusion of matter.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The surroundings are arranged to maintain two temperature reservoirs and two electric reservoirs.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] For an imagined, but not actually possible, thermodynamic equilibrium, heat transfer from the hot reservoir to the cold reservoir would need to be prevented by a specifically matching voltage difference maintained by the electric reservoirs, and the electric current would need to be zero.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] For a steady state, there must be at least some heat transfer or some non-zero electric current.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The two modes of energy transfer, as heat and by electric current, can be distinguished when there are three distinct bodies and a distinct arrangement of surroundings.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] But in the case of continuous variation in the media, heat transfer and thermodynamic work cannot be uniquely distinguished.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This is more complicated than the often considered thermodynamic processes, in which just two respectively homogeneous subsystems are connected.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] In 1854, Lord Kelvin found relationships between the three coefficients, implying that the Thomson, Peltier, and Seebeck effects are different manifestations of one effect (uniquely characterized by the Seebeck coefficient).
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] where T is the absolute temperature, ${\mathcal {K}}$ is the Thomson coefficient, $\Pi$ is the Peltier coefficient, and S is the Seebeck coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This relationship is easily shown given that the Thomson effect is a continuous version of the Peltier effect.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This relation expresses a subtle and fundamental connection between the Peltier and Seebeck effects.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Thomson coefficient is unique among the three main thermoelectric coefficients because it is the only one directly measurable for individual materials.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The Peltier and Seebeck coefficients can only be easily determined for pairs of materials; hence, it is difficult to find values of absolute Seebeck or Peltier coefficients for an individual material.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] If the Thomson coefficient of a material is measured over a wide temperature range, it can be integrated using the Thomson relations to determine the absolute values for the Peltier and Seebeck coefficients.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] This needs to be done only for one material, since the other values can be determined by measuring pairwise Seebeck coefficients in thermocouples containing the reference material and then adding back the absolute Seebeck coefficient of the reference material.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] For more details on absolute Seebeck coefficient determination, see Seebeck coefficient.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] The efficiency of such devices varies on several conditions, including its environment and the device in question.
[src:thermocouples/thermoelectric-effect] However, they roughly operate at efficiencies as low as 5% or sometimes as high as 12%.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] A **thermopile** or a **thermoelectric pile** is a device that converts thermal energy into electrical energy.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] It is composed of several thermocouples connected usually in series or, less commonly, in parallel.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Such a device works on the principle of the thermoelectric effect, i.e., generating a voltage when its dissimilar metals (thermocouples) are exposed to a temperature difference.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Thermocouples operate by measuring the temperature differential from their junction point to the point in which the thermocouple output voltage is measured.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Once a closed circuit is made up of more than one metal and there is a difference in temperature between junctions and points of transition from one metal to another, a current is produced as if generated by a difference of potential between the hot and cold junction.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] A thermopile usually consists of multiple thermocouples connected electrically in series and thermally in parallel, with junctions distributed between two isothermal regions.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Each thermocouple produces a small voltage proportional to the temperature difference between its hot and cold junctions.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] By connecting many thermocouples, the voltages are summed, yielding an output that scales with both the temperature gradient and the number of junctions.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Owing to their passive operation, thermopiles are widely used in non-contact infrared thermometry, energy harvesting, and process monitoring applications.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Thermopiles do not respond to absolute temperature, but generate an output voltage proportional to a local temperature difference or temperature gradient.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] The amount of voltage and power are very small and they are measured in millivolts and milliwatts using controlled devices that are specifically designed for such purpose.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] They are also used in heat flux sensors and pyrheliometers and gas burner safety controls.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] The output of a thermopile is usually in the range of tens or hundreds of millivolts.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] As well as increasing the signal level, the device may be used to provide spatial temperature averaging.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] Thermopiles are also used to generate electrical energy from, for instance, heat from electrical components, solar wind, radioactive materials, laser radiation or combustion.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] The process is also an example of the Peltier effect (electric current transferring heat energy) as the process transfers heat from the hot to the cold junctions.
[src:thermocouples/thermopile] There are also the so-called thermopile sensors, which are power meters based on the principle that the optical or laser power is converted to heat and the resulting increase in temperature is measured by a thermopile.
